data.content:
Yes — the direct cast `(EmailHandler)result` will throw an `InvalidCastException` on failure, so `Assert.IsNotNull` never actually catches a wrong type. Use `Assert.IsInstanceOfType` instead:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void Create_ReturnsCorrectHandler()
{
    var factory = new HandlerFactory();
    var result = factory.Create("email");

    Assert.IsInstanceOfType<EmailHandler>(result);
    var handler = (EmailHandler)result;
    Assert.AreEqual("email", handler.Type);
}
```

**Why this is better:**
- `IsInstanceOfType<T>` fails with a clear message (expected vs actual type) instead of an unhandled exception
- The cast after the assertion is now guaranteed safe
- If you only need the type check (not `handler.Type`), you can drop the cast entirely
